78","1332":"1332","1376":"1376","about 1378":"circa 1378","about 1376":"circa 1376","about 1374":"circa 1374","1406":"1406","1405":"1405","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1356–before 1385":"1356–before 1385","1356–1385":"1356–1385","1359–1406":"1359–1406","1348–Male":"1348–Deceased","1376–1405":"1376–1405","1332–1378":"1332–1378","before 1385":"before 1385","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1356":"1356","1378":"1378","1332":"1332","1376":"1376","about 1378":"about 1378","about 1376":"about 1376","about 1374":"about 1374","1406":"1406","1405":"1405","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Colton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from any of various places called Colton in England. Examples in Norfolk, Staffordshire, and North Yorkshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (or the cognate Old Norse <i>Koli</i>; see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The place so named in Somerset has as its first element the Old English personal name <i>Cūla</i> (of uncertain origin). The one in Cumbria has a river name apparently derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘hazel’. This English name is also common in Ireland; it was the name of a bishop of Derry in 1397. There seems also to have been confusion with   Culliton  .","Scottish and Irish (Monaghan): shortened and altered form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, ‘son of <i>Haldan</i>’, see   Haldane  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Culton","meanings":["Scottish (Kirkcudbrightshire): variant of   Colton   or   Culliton  ."]},{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colten","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Colton  ."]},{"name":"Coulton","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Colton  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anne de Colton was born in 1356, in Colton, Yorkshire, England as the daughter of William de Colton I. She married John de Chamond about 1374, in Colton, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died before 1385, in her hometown."},"et":{"1356–before 1385":"1356–enne 1385","1356–1385":"1356–1385","1359–1406":"1359–1406","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1376–1405":"1376–1405","1332–1378":"1332–1378","before 1385":"enne 1385","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1356":"1356","1378":"1378","1332":"1332","1376":"1376","about 1378":"umbes 1378","about 1376":"umbes 1376","about 1374":"umbes 1374","1406":"1406","1405":"1405","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, England","Colton, Selby, North Yorkshire, England":"Colton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, 